{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e2181d04-f18a-4cdd-b52c-491ce2124e30","content":"The directory is empty, so I'll provide the configuration directly based on .NET 11 NativeAOT crash dump requirements.\n\n## Configuration\n\nFor NativeAOT, the runtime needs to be told where `createdump` lives (since it's not bundled in the default location) and where to write dumps. Here are the pod spec changes:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nspec:\n  # Allow time for dump generation before SIGKILL\n  terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 120\n\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 4Gi\n\n  containers:\n    - name: your-app\n      env:\n        # Enable automatic crash dump on unhandled exception / SIGSEGV / SIGABRT\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n          value: \"1\"\n        # Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n          value: \"4\"\n        # Point the runtime to your createdump location\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n          value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n        # Dump file path (%p = PID, %t = timestamp)\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n          value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\"\n        # Optional: enable createdump diagnostics logging\n        - name: DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics\n          value: \"1\"\n\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add:\n            # Required: createdump uses ptrace to attach to the crashing process\n            - SYS_PTRACE\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Setting | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` | NativeAOT doesn't bundle `createdump` — you must point it to `/opt/tools/createdump` |\n| `SYS_PTRACE` | `createdump` uses `ptrace()` to read process memory; without this capability it silently fails |\n| `emptyDir` volume | Dumps survive container restarts; `sizeLimit` prevents node disk pressure |\n| `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 120` | Full dumps of large heaps take time — prevents Kubernetes from sending SIGKILL before the dump completes |\n| `DbgMiniDumpType=4` | Full dump gives the best post-mortem debugging; use `2` (Heap) if storage is tight |\n\n> **Tip:** Once dumps land in `/tmp/dumps`, collect them with a sidecar (e.g. upload to blob storage) or use `kubectl cp` before the pod is evicted. You can turn off `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` once you've confirmed dumps are being generated correctly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0785ccb9-5f72-461d-90b0-de88f0366656","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is just a scratch workspace. Let me provide the user with the correct configuration based on my knowledge of .NET NativeAOT crash dump collection in Kubernetes.\n\nFor NativeAOT .NET apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps. Key considerations:\n\n1. **NativeAOT and createdump**: In NativeAOT, the runtime doesn't automatically invoke `createdump` on crash like CoreCLR does. You need to configure it differently.\n\n2. For .NET 8+, NativeAOT supports crash dumps via environment variables. Starting with .NET 8, NativeAOT apps can use `createdump` but the mechanism is different from CoreCLR.\n\n\n3. The relevant environment variables for NativeAOT crash dumps include `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` to enable generation, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to specify the dump type, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` for the output path, and `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` for diagnostics. However, the actual crash dump mechanism for NativeAOT differs from what I initially outlined.\n\nFor .NET 8 and later, `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` does work with NativeAOT, and you'll need to pair it with `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` to specify the dump location. The `createdump` tool can also be used if you set up the appropriate signal handler. Starting in .NET 9, `DOTNET_EnableCrashReport` generates a JSON crash report alongside the dump file.\n\nIn a Kubernetes environment, I need to configure an `emptyDir` volume to persist crash dumps since the container filesystem is ephemeral, then set these environment variables in the container spec and ensure the necessary permissions are in place.\n\nFor the technical details: `createdump` requires the `SYS_PTRACE` capability to attach to the process, and I should avoid relying on `/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern` since that's controlled at the node level. The `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` variable can point to a custom location if needed. For .NET 11 specifically, the key variables are `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` for full dumps, which gives the best debugging information.\n\nI'm also checking whether `DOTNET_EnableCrashReport` applies here—it generates managed crash reports but that's primarily a CoreCLR feature. For NativeAOT in .NET 8+, the dump mechanism works differently, so I need to set `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` to point to where the user has placed `createdump` at `/opt/tools/createdump`.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the Kubernetes configuration changes needed: setting the environment variables on the container, mounting a volume for the dumps, granting `SYS_PTRACE` capability, and potentially adjusting the termination grace period.","outputTokens":1751,"requestId":"6012:2E8AE9:DD0903:1004B52:69EACA71"},"id":"3e33e215-48ed-49c8-b91d-ecdb4c37695e","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:41.967Z","parentId":"3a047810-628c-4881-ae8b-a0c6f424b315"}
